Intercept (1.543e-01)

  • The intercept represents the log-odd of customer current increases by 1.543e-01 when all predictors are at zero

1. Tenure (-0.655681, p < 0.001)

  • *A unit increase in tenure leads to a decrease in the initial odds of left customer by a factor of exp(-0.655681)

  • Guidance: Encourage customer loyalty through long-term engagement. Implement strategies that reward longer service, such as loyalty programs or tiered benefits based on tenure.

2. Senior Citizen (0.437057, p < 0.001)

  • Being a senior citizen increases the odds of leaving by a factor of exp(0.437057) compared to non-senior customers, all else remains the same.

  • Guidance: Tailor services and support to the unique needs of senior citizens. Provide simplified billing options, dedicated customer support, and services that cater to their preferences.

3. Phone Service (Yes: -0.604042, p < 0.001)

-The probability of default left for customers with phone service is lower than that for those without phone service, all else being same.

Guidance: Offer discounts for customers who combine phone service with other plans

4. Internet Service - Fiber Optic (1.295157, p < 0.001)

  • The probability of default left for customers with fiber optic internet is higher than for those with DSL internet, all else being same

Guidance: Enhance the reliability and performance of fiber optic internet service. Address common pain points through proactive customer support and service improvements.

5. Internet Service - No (-0.922199, p < 0.001)

  • The probability of default left for customers without internet service is essentially the same as those with DSL internet, given the insignificant coefficient. All else being same.

Guidance: Focus on maintaining satisfaction among customers without internet service, as they are already a loyal segment

6. Contract Length (One Year: -0.803419, p < 0.001 | Two Years: -1.914403, p < 0.001)

  • The probability of deafult left for customers on one-year contracts is lower than that for those on month-to-month contracts, all else being same.

-The probability of left for customers on two-year contracts is significantly lower than that for those on month-to-month contracts, all esle being same.

-Guidance: Offer discounts for one- or two-year contracts.

7. Paperless Billing (Yes: 0.395031, p < 0.001)

  • The probability of left for customers using paperless billing is higher than for those using traditional paper billing, all else being same

  • Guidance: Simplify the paperless billing process and clearly communicate its benefits

8. Total Charges (0.005685, p = 0.22, Not Significant)

  • There is no strong evidence that the total amount spent significantly affects whether a customer continues or leaves.

  • Guidance: While total charges may not be a direct predictor, focus on delivering value to customers. Ensure that customers perceive the services they receive as worth the cost.

Part 8 - Q5

Provide justification by evaluating costs and benefits of your incentive scheme. Costs will be the dollar amount in incentives given (for example). Benefits will be the revenues from these customers if they stay with your company. Compute the net benefits from your incentive scheme. Make a case in your report to your upper management for implementing your scheme.

Cost-Benefit Justification for Incentive Scheme

num_customers <- 154

monthly_revenue_loss <- 11988.2

# Incentive details
monthly_discount <- 15        # $15 discount per month
incentive_duration <- 3       # 3 months
incentive_per_customer <- monthly_discount * incentive_duration
total_incentive_cost <- num_customers * incentive_per_customer

# Revenue retained if customers stay for 3 months
total_revenue_retained <- monthly_revenue_loss * incentive_duration

# Net benefit
net_benefit <- total_revenue_retained - total_incentive_cost

"Total Incentive Cost:"
## [1] "Total Incentive Cost:"
total_incentive_cost
## [1] 6930
"Total Revenue Retained (3 months):"
## [1] "Total Revenue Retained (3 months):"
total_revenue_retained
## [1] 35964.6
"Net Benefit:"
## [1] "Net Benefit:"
net_benefit
## [1] 29034.6

Summary Breakdown of the Cost-Benefit Justification

1. Customer and Revenue Details

  • We got to know that there is a chance that on average 154 customers might leave

  • Each month, their departure would result in a revenue loss of $11,988.2.

2. Incentive Program

  • To retain customers, we offer a $15 discount per month.

  • The discount is provided for 3 months.

  • The total discount per customer over 3 months: 153 = 45

  • The total cost of the incentive for all customers:15445=6,930

3. Revenue Retention

  • If these customers stay, we retain revenue for 3 months.

  • Total revenue retained: 11,988.23=35,964.6

4. Net Benefit Calculation

  • Net Benefit = Total Revenue Retained - Total Incentive Cost

  • 35,964.6 6,930= 29,034.6

Conclusion: The incentive program costs $6,930 but helps retain $35,964.6 in revenue.The net benefit is $29,034.6, meaning the incentive is highly beneficial.

Incentive Program Recommendation:

  • Spending $6,930 on customer incentives will save us $35,964.60 in revenue over the next quarter - giving us a clear profit of $29,034.60.

  • Beyond the numbers, keeping existing customers is simply smart business. These customers already know and trust us. Theyre more likely to stick around long-term, recommend us to friends, and cost far less to maintain than finding new buyers.

  • This program protects our regular income while strengthening relationships with people who already value our services.
